      "id": 351374,
      "is_answer_order_important": false,
      "stimulus_html": "",
      "stem_html": "<p>Look at the following electrostatic potential map of methylamine, a substance responsible for the odor of rotting fish, and tell the direction of polarization of the C–N bond:</p>\n<img class=\"scaled-down-30\" src=\"https://exercises.openstax.org/rails/active_storage/blobs/proxy/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaHBBanNRIiwiZXhwIjpudWxsLCJwdXIiOiJibG9iX2lkIn19--0f3b4dbcec7c26937fc1408cf5bc1f8a8f685f28/OChem_02_01_005.jpg\" alt=\"The chemical structure and ball stick model of methylamine, plus an electron density map showing highest density near nitrogen.\">",
      "answers": [],
      "hints": [],
      "formats": [
        "free-response"
      ],
      "combo_choices": [],
      "collaborator_solutions": [
        {
          "images": [],
          "solution_type": "detailed",
          "content_html": "<p>The nitrogen is electron-rich, and the carbon is electron-poor.</p>\n<img src=\"https://exercises.openstax.org/rails/active_storage/blobs/proxy/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaHBBandRIiwiZXhwIjpudWxsLCJwdXIiOiJibG9iX2lkIn19--3692e4b1a568b6cda68774e8e7fa68e5542e76f8/OChem_02_EC_202.jpg\" alt=\"The chemical structure of methylamine where the direction of the dipole moment points from carbon toward nitrogen.\">"
        }
